  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 889faa658c7b2c94ea4fff939bf8022e, type: 3}
  m_Name: DialogNPCArmourer
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  Name: Patrizio
  Icon: {fileID: 7416670922274956215, guid: 67e11902f9a599344b5dc2f4b5a33db5, type: 3}
  HasInteraction: 0
  interactionType: 0
  Greeting: Patrick The Armourer (Brian 11labs)
  Day1Dialog:
  - "My father and I spent our lives shaping iron.  Hinges for doors, nails for scaffolds,
    blades for lords. That kind of work gives people a sense of safety.\nHere, I
    make pieces that send men back into fire. I tell myself it protects them, but
    I know it only delays something worse.\nThis is just the beginning. The guns
    haven\u2019t found their range yet. By tomorrow, more guns will find their range
    into our fort."
  Day2FirstTimeDialog:
  - "When armour comes back to me, I can read how a man met his end. A crushed rim
    means stone fragments. A torn plate means a shot caught him turning. You learn
    to see death in shapes.\nBy tomorrow, I\u2019ll start recognising my own work
    among the broken. I\u2019m not sure a man should know that."
  Day2MetBeforeDialog:
  - "Yesterday I mentioned that more guns will find their range, be careful out there
    boy!\r\nA helmet came in\u2014a piece I made years ago. Musket hole right through
    the brow. The poor lad must\u2019ve lifted his head an inch too high.\r\nBy tomorrow,
    recognising old pieces won\u2019t disturb me. That frightens me more than the
    hole."
  Day3FirstTimeDialog:
  - "I worked at the forge in Birgu before this. My father still does.  He is old
    and slower now. He taught me that an armourer\u2019s duty is to keep people safe.\r\nOut
    here, safety is a story we tell each other so we don\u2019t falter. We are patching
    steel still warm with someone's blood."
  Day3MetBeforeDialog:
  - "Do you remember that helmet I told you about? Today more arrived\u2014some with
    cloth, some with skin and pieces of brain still trapped in the seams.\r\nI can
    wash oil off metal. Blood is another matter. My hands look clean, but I still
    see red in the creases.\r\nTomorrow, I doubt I\u2019ll notice."
  Day4FirstTimeDialog:
  - "The guns are measured today. That means someone experienced is directing them\u2014someone
    who understands patience.\r\nWhen fire becomes accurate, my repairs stop being
    reassurance and start being prolongation. I\u2019m no coward, but I know that
    I am only delaying the inevitable."
  Day4MetBeforeDialog:
  - "It\u2019s a comfort seeing a familiar face still walking. Not many can claim
    that after last few days.\r\nThe walls shook, and men shook with them. Someone
    new must be among the Ottoman ranks\u2014someone who has done this before.\r\nI
    don't think this fort will hold for much longer."
  Day5FirstTimeDialog:
  - "You\u2019ve come when there\u2019s nearly nothing left to mend. That\u2019s
    not a sign of strength\u2014it\u2019s a sign there aren\u2019t enough bodies
    left to wear what I make.\r\nBy tomorrow, this forge will be abandoned or silent.
    I doubt I\u2019ll see Birgu again. The crossings are watched, and names don\u2019t
    matter anymore.\r\nI have to accept my faith.  I will die here."
  Day5MetBeforeDialog:
  - "So you\u2019re still breathing, I am glad. Half the defenders aren\u2019t. I
    used to think my work kept men alive. Now I think it keeps them present long
    enough to suffer."
  Day1Audio: {fileID: 8300000, guid: 575c11d032cf97741be85e7f4176f0a5, type: 3}
